{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MSA6Uh2DKY67YrPduLcQYP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the clause extractor correctly identifies terms. Is this a single module's logic or multiple modules? The clause extractor is one of the three independent reviewers. The question is whether this is about the extractor's own logic/output quality.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, subprocess involved.\n- LLM-DEP: The clause extractor is described as an \"AI reviewer\" - it identifies key terms. \n\nThe extraction quality depends entirely on what the real LLM produces, and I can't mock whether it will catch indirect or euphemistic language. This is agentic behavior - the correctness is non-deterministic and tied to the actual model's semantic understanding.\n\n**Behavior 2: The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.**\n\n- LLM-DEP: \"even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic\" - this strongly implies semantic understanding that only a real LLM can provide. A mock would just return predetermined outputs and not test whether the model actually understands indirect language.\n- This is clearly Agentic.\n\n**Behavior 3: The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.**\n\n- LLM-DEP: \"correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements\" - this is a quality/correctness claim about an AI reviewer's output. The compliance checker is another AI reviewer. This depends on real LLM judgment about regulatory compliance.\n- This is clearly Agentic.\n\n**Behavior 4: When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (e.g., extractor says \"standard\" but risk assessor says \"high risk\"), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the merge step logic - data transformation and merging logic. The failure mode is: given two conflicting assessments, does the system preserve both with proper attribution?\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess calls needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No - the merge step receives structured outputs from the reviewers. With fixed inputs (two conflicting assessments), the merge logic is deterministic and can be tested with mock structured outputs as fixtures.\n- This is Unit level testing - I'm checking whether the merge function correctly combines multiple reviewer outputs given fixed inputs.\n\nFor the full pipeline behavior, this is an end-to-end test involving dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting their results, and merging them into a unified report. The key concern is whether any findings get lost during dispatch, collection, or merging. While I could mock the reviewer outputs to verify the pipeline wiring, the requirement specifies \"for a real contract,\" which suggests actual AI calls are needed. This is a multi-step integration test that depends on real LLM behavior.\n\nLooking at the test taxonomy, I'm categorizing each behavior: the clause extractor and risk assessor are agentic tests because they require real LLM quality; the compliance checker is also agentic for the same reason; the merge step is a unit test since it's pure logic with fixed inputs; and the full pipeline is a workflow test because it chains multiple agentic steps in parallel followed by a merge operation.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels to each behavior based on how likely they are to fall into each test category. The clause extractor leans heavily agentic at 0.80 with some workflow uncertainty. The risk assessor detecting indirect language is even more clearly agentic at 0.90. The compliance checker is similarly high at 0.88 agentic.\n\nFor the merge step that preserves conflicts, this is primarily a unit test concern at 0.80 since I can construct fixed inputs with predetermined conflicting assessments and verify the deterministic merge logic handles them correctly.\n\nThe full pipeline running end-to-end is almost entirely workflow-dependent at 0.80, with small chances it's integration or system-level.\n\nNow I'm working through the test descriptions and justifications, starting with behavior 4 where the merge logic is fundamentally unit-testable because the inputs and outputs are deterministic and controllable.\n\nFor behavior 5, the workflow classification makes sense because this involves multiple agentic steps in sequence—three AI reviewers executing in parallel, then a merge step—which constitutes a full agent pipeline, and the test is really about whether that pipeline preserves all individual findings without loss.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9950,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9950},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"94629d5a-f417-4360-a7a5-67665178a623","uuid":"aed98627-f576-45ff-a4c7-a971622a4db7"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MSA6Uh2DKY67YrPduLcQYP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Ndwadcumy9XjGWLQCsCPf4","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Identifies all key terms' is a quality claim about an AI reviewer's extraction output. Correctness depends on what the real model produces — a mock returning fixed outputs trivially passes but tells you nothing about actual extraction fidelity. You cannot verify recall across parties/dates/obligations/penalties without running the real model on real contract text. REJECTION of lower levels: Unit/Integration — the merge and dispatch wiring is irrelevant here; failure is entirely inside the extractor's model inference. System — no external subprocess or real network is the bottleneck; the bottleneck is LLM output quality.","test_description":"Run the real clause extractor against a curated set of legal contract fixtures that contain known, ground-truth key terms (party names, effective dates, obligation clauses, penalty clauses). Assert that every ground-truth term appears in the extractor's output, measured by recall >= threshold. Vary contract styles (plain, legalese, template-heavy) to probe generalization.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The critical qualifier is 'even when indirect or euphemistic.' That semantic leap — recognizing that 'may seek remediation' means 'can sue you' — is exactly what only a real LLM can perform. A mock always returns the preconfigured answer and cannot fail on indirect phrasing. Running 100 times with the real model may vary on borderline cases. REJECTION of lower levels: Unit — the risk assessor's failure mode is not in its wiring or configuration parsing, it's in model comprehension of euphemism. Integration — in-process fakes substitute deterministic stub outputs and hide the semantic gap entirely.","test_description":"Feed the real risk assessor a set of contract snippets where problematic language is expressed indirectly (e.g., 'the counterparty retains the right to seek equitable relief' instead of 'counterparty can seek injunction'). For each snippet, assert that the risk assessor returns a non-zero risk flag consistent with the configured policy. Include both direct and euphemistic forms of the same risk to detect model-level recall failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0,"Agentic":0.88,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Correctly determines' compliance against jurisdiction-specific regulations is a quality assertion about AI reviewer judgment. Regulatory language is complex and context-dependent; a mock cannot exercise whether the model actually applies GDPR, CCPA, or industry-specific rules correctly. Different real-model runs may disagree on borderline compliance. REJECTION of lower levels: Unit — no deterministic algorithm produces jurisdiction compliance verdicts; the logic lives inside the model. Integration — an in-process fake would return a hardcoded verdict, making any test trivially pass regardless of the model's actual capability.","test_description":"Run the real compliance checker against contract fixtures with known compliance outcomes for specific jurisdictions (e.g., a GDPR-compliant DPA, a contract missing required CCPA disclosures). Assert that the checker's verdict (compliant/non-compliant) matches the ground-truth label for each fixture. Cover at least two jurisdictions with both compliant and non-compliant examples.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.86,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments, the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here lives entirely inside the merge function's algorithm — given two structured reviewer outputs that reference the same clause with different labels, does the merge function produce a result containing both entries with their source labels? That is a deterministic transformation of in-memory data structures. No LLM is involved in the merge step itself. REAL-INFRA: No OS, filesystem, subprocess, or network is involved. LLM-DEP: Reviewer outputs are treated as fixed inputs to the merge step — we provide them directly as test fixtures, bypassing any real model call. REJECTION of higher levels: Integration — the failure is not at a module handoff boundary; we can construct inputs directly without running the extractor or risk assessor. Agentic — merge logic is deterministic given fixed inputs.","test_description":"Construct two ReviewerOutput fixtures in-memory: one from the clause extractor labeling clause-7 as 'standard obligation' and one from the risk assessor labeling clause-7 as 'high risk — indemnification trap'. Call the merge function directly with these two outputs. Assert the merged report contains exactly two entries for clause-7, each preserving the source reviewer's label and attribution field. Also assert no other reviewer's findings are dropped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, merging into a unified report — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: Three independent AI reviewer steps execute (in parallel or sequence), each producing real LLM output, followed by a merge step that consumes all three. That is a full multi-agentic-step pipeline — exactly the Workflow criterion. REAL-INFRA + LLM-DEP: 'For a real contract' signals real model calls, not stubs. The failure mode being tested is end-to-end: findings dropped in dispatch, in async collection, or in merge are all in scope. REJECTION of lower levels: Agentic — a single-reviewer Agentic test cannot catch failures where one reviewer's output is silently dropped during parallel collection or merge. Integration — in-process fakes for all three reviewers would trivially pass by returning deterministic stubs; they cannot reveal timing, ordering, or result-collection bugs that emerge from real async LLM calls completing at different latencies.","test_description":"Run the full pipeline against a real contract document using all three live AI reviewers. After the pipeline completes, assert: (a) the unified report contains at least one finding attributed to each of the three reviewers (clause extractor, risk assessor, compliance checker); (b) total finding count in the report equals the sum of per-reviewer finding counts collected before merging; (c) no reviewer result object is null or empty. Use a contract fixture with known multi-reviewer coverage to make the assertions meaningful.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.8}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9950,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9950},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"94629d5a-f417-4360-a7a5-67665178a623","uuid":"5418ef82-807c-4e22-8c30-730a8edc9eef"}
